The paper deals with the construction of optimal binary Z-complementary pairs (ZCPs) which have applications in communications and radar. This falls under the information theory (cs.IT) and cryptography and security (cs.CR) sub-categories. The paper also mentions the use of Turyn's method, which is a technique used in coding theory and combinatorics, indicating a possible connection to the sub-categories of signal processing (cs.SI) and data structures and algorithms (cs.DS). Finally, the applications of ZCPs in communications and radar suggest a possible connection to the networking and internet architecture (cs.NI) sub-category.
